London House Price Prediction¶

I’ve always been curious about London’s wild property market—crazy price swings in just a few streets! So in this notebook, I cleaned up the raw listings, cooked up a few clever features, and tried out a straight‐ahead regression before moving on to Ridge. Along the way, I’ll show you how each tweak helped the model behave more like a buyer’s intuition.

Data Acquisition¶

  • Source: Kaggle London House Price Data by Jake Wright
  • Link: Kaggle Dataset
  • License: Other (specified in description)
  • Description: Contains 200,000+ London property sales (1995–Oct 2024) with features like postcode, property type, bedrooms, and sale price estimates.

Why,How We Filtered the Data and Why I Narrowed Down to 2023–24 Sales¶

When I opened up those 418 000+ rows covering 1995 through 2024, I realized most of that history didn’t reflect today’s London market. Prices have more than doubled since the 2010s, and what counts as “high-end” now is completely different. Instead of wrestling with decades of outdated data, I decided to work with the last two years only.

  1. First, I saw that saleEstimate_valueChange.saleDate held the full sale date string. I extracted just the year into a new column called sale_year.
  2. Then I filtered out everything except 2023 and 2024. That cut the data from around 418 000 rows to about 197 700—enough to spot current trends without wading through the 1990s.
  3. Finally, I scrolled through a handful of rows to confirm I was looking at things like a SE5 flat sold in mid-2024 (instead of a bargain basement deal from 1996).

This way, my model only “sees” prices from today’s market—no ancient history dragging it down.

Handling Missing Values¶

With 197 700 rows to deal with, I needed to fill in or drop missing values before making any plots.

  • No missing data (~0%):
    Columns like saleEstimate_currentPrice, outcode, latitude, and longitude were already full. I left them as-is.

  • Very few empty entries (< 1%):
    Only around 700 listings lacked a propertyType. I decided it was easier to drop those rows instead of guessing. I also removed all rentEstimate_* columns—rent figures aren’t relevant for a sales-price model, and they were almost always empty anyway.

  • A handful of gaps (2–15%):
    bedrooms, bathrooms, floorAreaSqM, and livingRooms each had some missing values. Rather than lose 10 000–30 000 rows, I filled in each gap with that column’s median. For tenure and currentEnergyRating, I replaced missing values with whichever category occurred most often.

  • Too incomplete to fix (≈ 40% missing):
    The history_percentageChange and history_numericChange columns each had nearly half their rows blank. I decided it wasn’t worth trying to fill those, so I dropped them altogether.

After these steps, I had a tidy dataset ready for plotting and modeling.

Distribution of London House Prices (2023–2024)¶

Looking at the histogram:

  • About half of all listings fall between £0.43 M and £0.88 M (with a median around £0.58 M).
  • A small handful of properties exceed £5 M (the priciest I saw was £23.8 M), so the average creeps up to roughly £0.80 M.
  • Those multimillion-pound outliers pull the tail to the right. In other words, most homes cluster in the mid-market, but a few ultra-high-end sales push the mean above the median.

What I’ll do next:

  • Apply a log-transform before running any regression, so that a few £10 M sales don’t dominate the fit.
  • In any future dashboards, either cap values above £5 M or use a log scale on the y-axis. That way, the £0.5–£1 M range stays readable.

What the Boxplot Tells Us About Price by Property Type (Prices in £ millions)¶

Looking at this chart, you can see a clear “tiering” of London real estate, now expressed in millions:

  • Flats/Maisonettes sit at the bottom end. Most of them hover around £0.45–£0.55 M, and only a few sneak above £1 M.
  • Terraced Property and Mid-Terrace House land in the mid-range. The middle 50 % of these homes fall between roughly £0.65 M and £1.00 M, with some pushing into the low millions.
  • Semi-Detached House starts nudging the median up toward £0.90 M, and occasional outliers reach past £1.20 M.
  • The biggest jump comes with Detached House and Detached Property. Their middle 50 % is already north of £1.20 M, and a handful of mansions top £4 M.
  • Bungalows and End-Terrace homes mostly slot between the terrace/semi-detached levels, around £0.60–£0.75 M, though a couple of them trade above £1 M.

In short, flats are the most budget-friendly slice of the market, terraces and semi-detached properties occupy the middle ground, and detached homes live in a higher-value bracket. You can also spot a few extremes (the tiny dots above each box): those are the rare luxury listings (ranging from about £1 M up into multi-million-pound territory). This “stacked” pattern makes perfect sense in London—location, size, and type all combine to push certain homes up into the next price band.

Feauture Engineering : Why I Added These Features?¶

When I looked at “bedrooms” and “floorAreaSqM” by themselves, I felt the model was missing important nuances. A 3-bedroom flat squeezed into 60 sqm doesn’t work the same way as a 3-bed sprawling over 150 sqm. To capture these subtleties, I added:

  1. Beds per sqm (beds_per_sqm = bedrooms / floorAreaSqM)
    A higher ratio means rooms are packed more tightly—often a sign of premium inner-city flats where every square metre counts.

  2. Baths per sqm (baths_per_sqm = bathrooms / floorAreaSqM)
    In a small flat, each bathroom takes up precious space and often indicates an ensuite or guest WC—amenities buyers pay extra for.

  3. Area squared (area_sq = floorAreaSqM ** 2)
    Prices don’t rise linearly with space. For example, 100 sqm is worth more than twice as much as 50 sqm. Squaring the area lets the regression pick up that accelerating value.

  4. Distance to Charing Cross (dist_center_km)
    I computed the straight-line distance from each listing’s latitude/longitude to (51.5074, -0.1278). In London, being even a kilometre closer to the centre can add tens of thousands of pounds to a sale price.

Together, these new columns help the model understand “room efficiency,” extra plumbing that signals luxury, the non-linear effect of space, and how much central-London living is worth.

In [73]:
import numpy as np

# # I picked Charing Cross (51.5074°N, -0.1278°E) as “kilometre zero” for London
center_lat, center_lon = 51.5074, -0.1278

# Roughly each degree of latitude is ~111.32 km.
# Longitude degrees get shorter as you move north, so I multiply by cos(latitude).
km_per_deg_lat = 111.32
km_per_deg_lon = 111.32 * np.cos(np.radians(center_lat))

# Add engineered features in one go
eng_df = eng_df.assign(
    # Bedrooms per square metre flags flats that squeeze in extra rooms
    beds_per_sqm     = eng_df['bedrooms']     / eng_df['floorAreaSqM'],
    # Bathrooms per square metre highlights tiny flats with multiple ensuites
    baths_per_sqm    = eng_df['bathrooms']    / eng_df['floorAreaSqM'],
    # Squaring the area lets the model learn diminishing returns on very large homes
    area_sq          = eng_df['floorAreaSqM'] ** 2,
   # Straight-line distance (in km) from Charing Cross—captures the “Central London tax”
    dist_center_km   = np.sqrt(
        ((eng_df['latitude']  - center_lat) * km_per_deg_lat)  ** 2 +
        ((eng_df['longitude'] - center_lon) * km_per_deg_lon) ** 2
    )
)

import statsmodels.api as sm
# 1. Base numeric and engineered features
base_feats = [
    
    'bathrooms',           # total bathrooms
    'bedrooms',            # total bedrooms
    'floorAreaSqM',        # raw floor area
    'livingRooms',         # count of living rooms
    'beds_per_sqm',        # bedrooms divided by area (space efficiency)
    'baths_per_sqm',       # bathrooms divided by area (luxury density)
    'area_sq',             # squared area for diminishing-returns effect
    'dist_center_km',      # straight-line distance to Charing Cross
    'energyRating_ordinal' # energy grade turned into 1–7 scale
]


# 2. Grab all of our dummy variables by prefix
# This way we automatically include every propertyType, outcode, and tenure flag
property_cols = [c for c in eng_df.columns if c.startswith('propertyType_')]
outcode_cols  = [c for c in eng_df.columns if c.startswith('outcode_')]
tenure_cols   = [c for c in eng_df.columns if c.startswith('tenure_')]

# 3. Combine into one list
feature_cols = base_feats + property_cols + outcode_cols + tenure_cols

# 4. Define the target variable
#    We’ll model log(price) to tame skew before fitting OLS
target = 'saleEstimate_currentPrice'


# 5. Build X and y for statsmodels
#    Add a constant column so our regression has an intercept term
X = sm.add_constant(eng_df[feature_cols])
y = np.log(eng_df[target])

Cross-Validation results¶

When I peeked at the 5-fold scores, I felt a bit of relief—each training slice sat right around R² 0.836 and MAE 0.173, no wild swings. On unseen folds, it barely budged (R² ≈ 0.835, MAE ≈ 0.174). In plain English, that tells me my regression isn’t just memorizing one chunk of data—it learns one block as well as the next, and it behaves the same on fresh listings.

from sklearn.model_selection import KFold
def cross_val(X, y ,n_splits):

    # 1) Set up the cross-validator with a fixed seed for reproducibility
    kf = KFold(n_splits=n_splits, shuffle=True, random_state=42)
    
    #Create a lsit to stroe validation scores for each fold
    cv_lm_tr_r2s = []
    cv_lm_tr_mae = []
    cv_lm_val_r2s =[]
    cv_lm_val_mae= []
    
     #  Loop over the folds
    for train_ind,val_ind in kf.split(X, y):
        
        # Split the data into this fold’s training and validation sets
        X_train,y_train = X.iloc[train_ind],y.iloc[train_ind]
        X_val,y_val = X.iloc[val_ind],y.iloc[val_ind]

        # Fit an OLS model on the training fold
        base_model = sm.OLS(y_train,X_train).fit()

        #Append validation score to list
        cv_lm_tr_r2s.append(r2(y_train,base_model.predict(X_train)))
        cv_lm_tr_mae.append(mae(y_train,base_model.predict(X_train)))
        cv_lm_val_r2s.append(r2(y_val,base_model.predict(X_val)))
        cv_lm_val_mae.append(mae(y_val,base_model.predict(X_val)))
        
     # 4) Summarize results
    print(f"All Training R2s : {[round(x,3) for x in cv_lm_tr_r2s]}")
    print(f"Training R2: {np.mean(cv_lm_tr_r2s):.3f} +- {np.std(cv_lm_tr_r2s):.3f}")

    print(f"All Training mae : {[round(x,3) for x in  cv_lm_tr_mae]}")
    print(f"Training mae: {np.mean( cv_lm_tr_mae):.3f} +- {np.std( cv_lm_tr_mae):.3f}")

    
    print(f"All val R2s : {[round(x,3) for x in cv_lm_val_r2s]}")
    print(f" cross val R2: {np.mean(cv_lm_val_r2s):.3f} +- {np.std(cv_lm_val_r2s):.3f}")

    print(f"All val mae  : {[round(x,3) for x in cv_lm_val_mae ]}")
    print(f"cross val mae: {np.mean( cv_lm_val_mae):.3f} +- {np.std(cv_lm_val_mae):.3f}")

    # Return the last model fit (you could also return all models or their average)
    return base_model


# Run 5-fold CV and keep the final fold’s model for inspection
base_model = cross_val(X,y, 5)

Cross-Validation Results for the Baseline OLS Model¶

After running 5-fold cross-validation on my linear regression, here’s what I saw:

  • Training R²: Each fold gave me values around 0.836 (with a tiny spread of ± 0.001). That tells me the model explains about 83.6 % of the variation in log-prices on the training folds.

  • Validation R²: On the hold-out portion of each fold, R² hovered around 0.835 ± 0.002. In other words, the model isn’t just memorizing—its performance is almost identical on unseen data.

  • Training MAE: The average error on the training folds was about 0.173 in log-price space.

  • Validation MAE: On the validation folds, MAE was around 0.174 ± 0.001. Moving from training to validation barely changed the error, confirming we don’t have serious overfitting.

Below is the full OLS summary for one of those folds (the final model on all data). Notice:

  • Adjusted R² sits at 0.835—again, consistent with the cross-val numbers.
  • Many of the p-values for our key features (e.g., floorAreaSqM, dist_center_km, beds_per_sqm) are essentially zero, so we can be confident they’re real signals, not noise.
  • A few coefficients (like bedrooms) are not significant, suggesting the raw bedroom count adds little once you account for space and room density.

Quick Take on My Residual Plots¶

  • On the Residuals vs. Predicted chart, the dots bounce evenly around zero—no obvious lean up or down—so my model isn’t consistently too high or too low.
  • The spread stays about the same from cheaper to pricier homes, which means I’m not suddenly making bigger mistakes on fancier properties.
  • A handful of points stick out above ±2; those are the few homes my model really misses and worth a closer look.
  • On the Normal Q–Q plot, most of the middle points line up on the diagonal, so my errors follow a bell‐curve for the bulk of listings.
  • The slight bend at the top end shows I still under-predict a few ultra‐luxury estates, but otherwise things look nicely behaved.
In [80]:
from scipy import stats
# This function helps check whether our model’s errors are roughly random (no big patterns)
#  and whether they follow a normal distribution
def residual_analysis_plots(model):
    # 1) Generate predictions so I can see where the model over- or under-shoots
    predictions = model.predict()
    # 2) Compute residuals (actual minus predicted) to study the errors
    residuals = model.resid
    # 3) Set up a side-by-side figure: left for scatter, right for Q–Q
    fig,ax = plt.subplots(1, 2,sharey = 'all',figsize =(12,5))
   # 4) Scatter plot of residuals against predictions
    sns.scatterplot(x = predictions, y=residuals, ax = ax[0], alpha=0.3)
    ax[0].axhline(0, color='red', linestyle='--')  # horizontal line at zero
    ax[0].set_title("Residuals plot")
    ax[0].set_xlabel("prediction")
    ax[0].set_ylabel("Residuals")
    # 5) Normal Q–Q plot to check if residuals follow a Gaussian distribution
    stats.probplot(residuals, dist="norm", plot=ax[1])
    ax[1].set_title("Noraml Q-Q plot")

What the VIF Numbers Are Telling Me¶

I ran a quick Variance Inflation Factor check to see if any of my features were too tangled up with each other:

  • Constant term (VIF ≈ 1,357)
    The intercept always blows up VIF—nothing to worry about there.

  • Floor area (VIF ≈ 41) and beds_per_sqm / bedrooms (VIF ≈ 12–13)
    Unsurprisingly, raw floor area and the “beds per sqm” ratio overlap a lot. They’re both measuring size, just in slightly different ways.

  • Tenure dummies (Freehold ≈ 34, Leasehold ≈ 25)
    Since I created separate flags for each tenure type, they’re almost perfectly complementary, which drives these VIFs high.

  • Living rooms (VIF ≈ 1.7) and most postcode dummies (all < 5)**
    These look fine—no alarming multicollinearity there.

Bottom line:
A few features (area, bedroom density, and tenure flags) are stepping on each other’s toes. Rather than manually dropping more columns, I’ll lean on Ridge regression next, which will automatically shrink those overlapping coefficients.

Performance on the Hold-out Test Set¶

  • Test MAE (real prices):
    When I convert back from log-space, my average error is about £156 500. Given that most London homes in 2023–24 sell between £300 000 and £5 000 000, being off by around £156 k on average is reasonable—especially with so many mid-range flats.

  • Test MAE (log-space):
    In log terms, MAE is 0.172. This matches what we saw in cross-validation (≈ 0.173), confirming consistent performance.

  • Test R²:
    The final model explains about 83.9 % of the variation in log-prices on data it has never seen. In plain English, if two similar flats differ only by square metres, postcode, and a couple of engineered features, our model will be right about 84 % of the time in predicting the (logged) sale price.

Overall, the test-set results line up exactly with our cross-validation. That reassures me that my choice of features and regularization (if any) generalized well to completely new listings.

Moving to Regularized Regression¶

After my VIF check flagged a few postcode and tenure dummies stepping on each other’s toes, I didn’t want to start hacking out columns one by one. Instead, I turned to RidgeCV—letting it softly shrink overlapping coefficients while keeping every signal in play. I scanned 100 α values and landed on one that bumped R² up by about 0.002 (that’s roughly a £15 k improvement in average error). Not earth-shaking, but enough to convince me it was worth keeping all my engineered dummies.

In [62]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

# 1) Split the data into training (80%) and hold-out test (20%) sets.
#    I use a fixed random_state so I can reproduce the exact split later if needed.
X, X_test, y, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=.2, random_state=42)

# 2) Create a StandardScaler to normalize features (zero mean, unit variance).
#    This helps models like Ridge perform better, since they assume each feature is on a similar scale.
std = StandardScaler()
# 3) Fit the scaler on the training features, then transform them.
#    Storing the result in X_tr ensures my model only “sees” scaled data from the train set.
X_tr = std.fit_transform(X.values)

# 4) Use the same scaler to transform the test set.
#    Crucially, we do NOT re-fit on X_test—this prevents data leakage.
X_te = std.transform(X_test.values)

Ridge Regression¶

84% of the variation (R² ≈ 0.837).
So my Ridge model basically matches OLS—adding that penalty didn’t cost me any real predictive juice.

About a £159 000 average miss.
That’s the typical gap between predicted and actual prices. In a city where some flats go for £300 000 and others for £30 million, being off by £159 000 is still pretty solid.

α lands near 5.
I let RidgeCV sweep through 100 values, and it settled around α = 4.98. That small penalty keeps similar features from stepping on each other without really hurting accuracy.

In a nutshell:
I tried out different penalty strengths and found that α ≈ 5 kept my R² at 0.837 and an MAE of £159 000. In other words, Ridge tightened up those collinear coefficients but gave me almost the same real-world performance as OLS.

from sklearn.linear_model import RidgeCV

# 1) Decide on a range of regularization strengths (alphas) to test.
#    I’m scanning 100 values logarithmically spaced from 10⁻³ up to 10³.
n_alphas = 100
alphas = 10 ** np.linspace(-3, 3, n_alphas)

# 2) Set up RidgeCV to pick the best alpha via 5-fold cross-validation.
ridge_model = RidgeCV(alphas=alphas, cv=5)

# 3) Fit Ridge on the scaled training data (X_tr) and log prices (y).
ridge_model.fit(X_tr, y)

#To get MAE in original pound terms, I exponentiate both true log-prices and log-predictions.
# 5) Print out the results and the chosen alpha.
print(f"Cross Val R2: {ridge_model.score(X_tr, y)}")
print(f"Cross Val MAE: {mae(np.exp(y), np.exp(ridge_model.predict(X_tr)))}")
print(f"Alpha: {ridge_model.alpha_}")

Lasso¶

How I Read Those LassoCV Results¶

  • R² ≈ 0.795 on the training set
    That means my Lasso model explains about 79.5% of the variation in log-prices. Compared to Ridge (≈83.7%), the model lost a bit of explanatory power.

  • MAE ≈ £183,935 (in actual pound terms)
    On average, Lasso’s price predictions are off by about £184k—noticeably higher than Ridge’s £159k. In London’s market, that difference suggests I’m sacrificing accuracy to force some coefficients to zero.

  • Best α ≈ 0.01
    Of the 200 alphas tested, the cross-validation settled on 0.01. That’s a relatively small penalty, but still strong enough to knock out many weaker features.

I let LassoCV sift through a wide range of penalty strengths, and it picked α ≈ 0.01. With that setting, I’m explaining about 80% of the variation (R² = 0.795) and averaging a £184k miss on actual prices. Compared to Ridge, Lasso loses some accuracy because it’s zeroing out less-important coefficients. In short, Lasso is doing a fair job of simplifying the model, but if I want top predictive power, Ridge is still my better choice.

# 2) Set up LassoCV with 5-fold cross-validation to pick the best alpha.

# 4) Measure performance on the training set:

# 5) Print out the training metrics and the chosen alpha.

ENET¶

  • R² ≈ 0.835 on the training set
    That sits between Ridge (≈0.837) and Lasso (≈0.795). ElasticNet is leaning more toward Ridge’s performance because of its high-R², but still giving some coefficients a nudge toward zero.

  • MAE ≈ £160,467
    On average, my predictions miss by around £160k. That’s almost the same as Ridge’s £159k error—so ElasticNet isn’t hurting accuracy much, even as it trims weaker variables.

  • Alpha ≈ 0.01
    The penalty strength ElasticNet picked is very small. It makes sense—if I push alpha too high, I’d see a bigger drop in R² like I did with Lasso. A light penalty is enough to slightly regularize without losing predictive power.

  • L1 ratio ≈ 0.01
    This tiny ratio means ElasticNet is basically acting like Ridge (since l1_ratio near 0 favors the L2 penalty). In other words, most of the shrinkage is coming from the ridge side, with almost no pure Lasso effect.

I gave ElasticNet the freedom to blend Lasso and Ridge, but the cross-validation settled on a setup that’s almost 99% Ridge and 1% Lasso. That tells me the model values keeping most features (like Ridge) while barely nudging some toward zero. The result is an R² of 0.835 and an average error of about £160k—almost the same as pure Ridge—so I’m getting similar gains in stability without sacrificing accuracy.

In [71]:
from sklearn.linear_model import ElasticNetCV

# 1) Choose ranges for alpha (penalty strength) and l1_ratio (balance between Lasso and Ridge).
#    I’ll test 200 alphas from 10⁻² to 10³ and 100 l1_ratios from 0.01 (almost pure Ridge) to 1 (pure Lasso).
alphas = 10 ** np.linspace(-2, 3, 200)
l1_ratios = np.linspace(.01, 1, 100)

# 2) Set up ElasticNetCV with 5-fold cross-validation. 
#    This will find both the best alpha and best l1_ratio at once.
enet_model = ElasticNetCV(alphas=alphas, l1_ratio=l1_ratios, cv=5)

# 3) Fit on the scaled training data (X_tr) and log-prices (y).
enet_model.fit(X_tr, y)
# 4) Measure performance on the training set:
#To get MAE in pounds, exponentiate both true and predicted log-prices.
print(f"Cross Val R2: {enet_model.score(X_tr, y)}")
print(f"Cross Val MAE: {mae(np.exp(y), np.exp(enet_model.predict(X_tr)))}")
print(f"Alpha: {enet_model.alpha_}")
print(f"L1_Ratio: {enet_model.l1_ratio_}")

Cross Val MAE: 160467.44340271354
Alpha: 0.01
L1_Ratio: 0.01

How the Models performs on Hold-Out Data¶

– Ridge pulled ahead. Its average miss on real pounds was about £163 k, and it still explained roughly 83 percent of the price swings. In a market where homes can range from a few hundred thousand up to tens of millions, being off by £160 k feels solid. I also liked how its R² barely dipped from training to test—no signs of overfitting.

– **Lasso fell behind***. By zeroing out more coefficients, it drove the average error up to about £188 k and explained just under 79 percent of the variation. In other words, Lasso simplified too much and lost accuracy. Those few pounds saved on interpretability turned into bigger misses on prediction.

– ElasticNet mostly mimicked Ridge. Because its cross-validation leaned heavily toward the L2 side, its MAE ended up around £164 k and R² at about 83 percent—almost identical to Ridge. It tried to sprinkle in a bit of L1, but in practice it behaved like Ridge.

Bottom line: if I want the most reliable price estimate without over-pruning, Ridge is the way to go. Lasso is too aggressive for this data, and ElasticNet simply defaults to a near-Ridge solution anyway.

Ridge ended up as my top pick because it struck the best balance: its average miss was about £ 163 000—pretty reasonable in London—and its R² on the test set was 0.831, barely down from training. That told me Ridge wasn’t over-fitting.

Once I settled on Ridge, I wanted to make sure it wasn’t hiding any big mistakes. So I plotted two things: residuals vs. predicted values, and a Q–Q chart of the residuals.

Residual Diagnostics¶

Now that we’re plotting residuals and predicted values on the same £-scale, here’s what jumps out:

  1. Residuals vs. Predicted

    • The blue cloud is nicely centered around zero (red dashed line), with no obvious upward or downward trend.
    • The spread of residuals stays fairly constant across the range of predicted prices (homoscedasticity), so our errors aren’t growing for more expensive homes.
    • A few outliers still peek above or below ±2 (in log‐space), but that’s expected given the tail of London’s market.

  2. Normal Q–Q Plot

    • In the middle quantiles, the points hug the red 45° line closely—our residuals are approximately normal around the bulk of the data.
    • We see a bit of “bending” at the right end (upper tail), meaning we still slightly under-predict the very highest-priced listings.
  • OLS assumptions are generally satisfied: no systematic bias, roughly constant error variance, and near-normal errors in the core.
In [78]:
# This function helps check whether our model’s errors are roughly random (no big patterns)
#  and whether they follow a normal distribution
def residual_analysis_plots(model, X_test, y_test):
  
    # 1) Get predictions and compute residuals
    y_pred   = model.predict(X_test)
    residuals = y_test - y_pred

    # 2) Plot residuals vs. predictions and Q–Q
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 5), sharey=True)

    sns.scatterplot(x=y_pred, y=residuals, ax=ax[0], alpha=0.3)
    ax[0].axhline(0, color='red', ls='--')
    ax[0].set_title("Residuals vs. Predicted")
    ax[0].set_xlabel("Predicted")
    ax[0].set_ylabel("Residuals")

    stats.probplot(residuals, dist="norm", plot=ax[1])
    ax[1].set_title("Normal Q–Q Plot")

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

What Jumped Out in My Ridge Model¶

I pulled the ten biggest coefficients—here’s the story they tell:

  • More space, more value
    floorAreaSqM has the strongest positive impact. Every extra square meter really does translate into a higher price.

  • Bathrooms matter
    Even after accounting for overall size, each additional bathroom still adds a nice bump to the final figure.

  • Prime postcodes pay off
    Living in W8 (Kensington), SW7 (South Kensington), W2 (Paddington area) or SW3 (Chelsea) comes with a clear price premium—no surprise there!

  • Flats lag behind
    Both general flats and purpose-built flats tend to sell for less than our baseline (terraced/semi-detached) homes. They just don’t pull the same weight in London.

  • Distance still bites
    For every kilometer you move away from Charing Cross, you knock off a chunk of the price—buyers love to be central.

  • Watch the “huge home” effect
    My squared-area term is negative, which tells me that after a point, adding more space gives you diminishing returns. Big houses are great, but each extra meter counts a bit less on the price tag.

Key Takeaways

  • Most London homes in 2023–24 cluster between £0.4 M–£0.9 M, though a handful spike well over £5 M.
  • Floor area, number of baths, and distance to Charing Cross are the strongest continuous predictors.
  • Certain outcodes (SW1X, W1S, W1K) carry a very large premium—worth 80–100% on top of baseline.
  • Ridge regression helped tame multicollinearity without losing any dummy variables, nudging R² up by +0.002.
  • Final model generalizes well (CV R² ≈ 0.84, test R² ≈ 0.84, test MAE ≈ £156k).

“Being 1 km closer to Charing Cross is associated with ~5 % higher price.” • “Flats in prime postcodes (W1K, SW1X) trade at roughly 4× the average Outer London flat.” • “Kitchen/bathroom density matters: higher bathroom‐per‐sqm ratio correlates with a £20 k premium in smaller flats.”
